metadata.description:

metadata.name: Punktwelt #136
metadata.description:
Continuing on the theme of color perception in Farbteiler, Punktwelt is an exploration of color interaction, projection and perceived depth, and the aesthetics of simple Boolean operations on form.

Each shape is the result of a single block, a rectangular cuboid, subjected to a series of Boolean subtractions with other blocks, and rendered in parallel projection, oblique or axonometric, in the abstract landscape of the Punktwelt.

Some have horizons, some have banded or striped backgrounds. The unnatural drawing order and chromatic differences of the individual faces sometimes yields illusory or paradoxical visual geometries.

Press ‚Äôs‚Äô to save a png. Press ‚Äô4‚Äô to export a high resolution png. Press ‚Äô8‚Äô to export a very high resolution png. Press ‚Äôe‚Äô to export an SVG file (may take some time and produce large files).

Aspect ratio variations are 4:5, 5:4, 2:3, 3:2 and 1:1.

Built in Javascript with p5.js, p5.svg and csg.js.

metadata.name: The Modern Depth #26
metadata.description:
there is a new horizon that shimmers and shines

a place which never was before, but there always seemed to be. 
You can see it from the top of any slope, or at the bottom any hole; you can feel it in your bones when you're tired, or be blinded by it when its bright. 
And this is why we must climb every mountain and how we'll map out all those stars. 
A shape made from Modern Depth, standing tall in front of us all.
And all the people that see it on a walk in the woods don't flinch,
they feel a strange connection to the Modern Depth that can be found. 
And most importantly, we don't abuse it because we know how to use it. ¬†

metadata.name: Impression of Rolling Sphere #177
metadata.description:
"Impression of Rolling Sphere" by UeShiba is a piece that has different interpretations and so many thoughts, ways of seeing it. The artist‚Äôs work inspires feelings and emotions from its beauty to the mindfulness of the subject. It is an interesting time as people see life primarily through a different lens.

The gallery explores what it means to have a relation with this painting, how one can perceive it differently, or how they can just appreciate it for what it is: a beautiful piece of art that may give you somatic sensations or even a philosophical thought.

I suggests that this small, sphere is impression of the universe and within ourselves, one can feel the flow of nature, communication between people and with life itself.

metadata.name: Liaisons Dangereuses #39
metadata.description:
"Liaisons dangereuses" is a creative exploration of implausible relations between figurative art and poetry. Our AI poet learned on the basis of texts about artists and their work. It memorized all subtleties of a language designed to describe visual emotions and artworks. This language is the tool for creating countless poems about artistic concepts, which range from techniques to materials to artists, etc. But the link is two-sided: if the poet is fed by art language, the concepts expressed by poems do, in turn, influence the appearance of the artwork. Color palettes, pattern types and the flow of the graphic composition are indeed determined by the semantics of the poem.
In each minting, the poet will produce either a short poem (a iambic 5-7-5 haiku  or a iambic cinquain according to Adelaide Crapsey style) or a single verse (either an alexandrine, or a iambic pentameter or an anapestic tetrameter). There are 625 artistic concepts that can trigger a poem, and each concept can generate countless different semantically coherent poems. The poet is completely "unchained": contents might be peaceful harmonic assertions as well as embarrassing, politically incorrect claims.

You can save to file the image by pressing the "s" key.

metadata.name: The Living Book #2 Moonrise #32
metadata.description:
I have been exploring the medium of print for years. Mixing etching, silk-screening, offset, photocopy, risography, drawing and painting to design and craft experimental art books.From the day digital, which had always fascinated me, took over my publishing practice, I always liked to create bridges between these two worlds.

The Living Books is part of this series of hybrid and experimental works where paper and digital resonate.

This issue #2 is made of 64 pages that will be minted by collectors. A book will eventually be printed and the pages will follow the mint order. Each page exists in a cover version (c) and a xerox version (x).

Controls :

‚Ä¢ Click to dive into each frame.
‚Ä¢ Press C to toggle cover mode.
‚Ä¢ Press X to toggle xerox mode.
‚Ä¢ Press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to make a capture and download a PNG with a resolution of x1, x2, x3 or x4.
